ssed the importance of the Liaison Officer for Emergency Management (LOEM), viewing the position as merely a liaison channel between OEM agencies and the White House. Mordecai Lee presents a revisionist history of OEM, focusing mostly on the record of the longest serving LOEM, Wayne Coy. Drawing upon largely unexamined archival sources, including the Roosevelt and Truman Presidential Libraries and the National Archives, Lee gives a precise account of what Coy actually did and, contrary to the conventional wisdom, concludes he was an important senior leader in the Roosevelt White House, engaging in management, policy, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xEconomic aspectszUnited States. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : World War II. 4aPolitics and Law : American Government. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Presidency, The. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847138940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438471389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438471389/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles